Right-wing populists in Austria have won 29 percent of the vote
The preliminary results showed that the early parliamentary elections in Austria had brought a significant weakening of the two parties that make up the current grand coalition, as well as a notable strengthening of the populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
The electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain the country's top political force, with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared with the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent, ended up even worse.
This is the worst result of the two major postwar parties; particularly for the People's Party, which triggered the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
In early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
But the voters were clearly punishing them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation was raised about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary meeting of the party leadership.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the way to the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the large SPÖ and ÖVP coalition.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPÖ) would have won 18 percent and the BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the socialists at the same time expressed fear of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, the BZÖ split in 2005) on a common government, which even prompted sanctions from the European Union.
Mr Haider, who has already said he is ready to work with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna on the national political scene, apparently focused on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but they lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
Clearly, no other party has passed the four percent threshold and has not entered parliament.
