Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons.
Long before Turkey was considering joining the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate its hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps from Asia, lies one of the finest relics of its fallen imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed in a neo-renaissance style by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu.
At least that's what the guides tell us.
The monument is mounted at the back of the platforms, with observation towers at each of its corners, as some German provincial town halls do.
The stones are dirty.
The whole building is in ruins.
But once inside the vaulted ticket office, we have no doubt about the size of the enterprise, which represents a passage to the west.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German association, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the game of imperialism, wanted to achieve its medieval ambitions of domination through this railway that reached Damascus, Baghdad and the land better known as Saudi Arabia.
But German imperialist ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Its railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, created by the cold war's frozen borders, is over.
The British and Imperial forces advanced beyond Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
But there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a train loaded with ammunition exploded destroying its subtle roof .
Turkish sources say this is sabotage.
Since then, it has been slowly falling into ruin, engulfed in the mystery of history.
But today, the railway passage to Anatolia and all the eastern points is at least symbolically used to highlight Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has created a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, caused by the cold war's frozen borders
Now it's time for a new commitment policy.
The Turkish government has remarkable relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To judge the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded a sleeping car to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit Turkish AKP MP Suat Kiniklioglu, one of the experts on foreign policy.
The next morning, after a 10-and-a-half-hour journey, shaken by noisy railroads that reminded me of the old world of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I finally arrived in the Turkish capital - presented as a new city of a new century, turning my back on its German past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots, represents an example of a change in Turkish consensus.
He suspected the West, and Washington in particular.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure, specifically built of stone and steel, in a developing neighborhood, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and many pastry shops where middle managers in suit-and-tie-dress - men and women - meet for morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could have been a centre-right politician from any other party in Europe.
He's got a suit, a tie, and he even has a black berry.
"The aim of this foreign policy is to now reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its home country.
Now she must look east and west at the same time.
Neither of us was.
She had to do both.
But then, at some point, I asked if Turkey should not choose.
"Turkey", he said, "does not want to have to choose between the two".
He then pointed out an aspect that almost everyone I spoke with has recited to me by heart: the Turkish railway does not only go to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, so it is as much an advantage for Europe and the United States as it is for Turkey itself.
With Turkey's integration, the message seems to draw a Europe traveling metaphorically on the railways to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another sleepless night, I thought of these two Germans, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched the building being built 100 years ago.
They would have been surprised to see that the European ambitions of the Middle East could be largely in the hands of Turkey.
As I waited at the terminal, the ferry to cross the Bosphorus, I remembered the time when Turkey had been called "the sick man of Europe".
At least there is no doubt about the continent that could claim this fascinating country.
