The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It's called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and it represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center have designed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During their flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bees' eyes, which can see at an angle of over 300 degrees and in all directions, allowing them to fly uninterrupted within their own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles at a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by twisting its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other system in existence is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Displacement Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow, and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device only has to process information and act on that data.
It doesn't need to store the information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabyte".
This is the first car to develop new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced into production cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding road obstacles.
