Morgan Stanley opens its capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley has announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), Japan's first bank, to pay out $9 billion to take 21% of its capital, a news welcomed by a sharp drop in its stock price.
A week after unveiling a provisional agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's common stock at a unit price of $25.25, or a total of $3 billion.
The retained price is 19% below the carrying amount of the securities at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said the overall transaction would be based on an average unit price of $29 or 28% above its current price.
However, Morgan Stanley's stock was down 6.79% to $23.07 at around 5:00 p.m.
"This strategic alliance is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to holding bank status", explained John Mack, the group's managing director in the US.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new status last week, which should allow it to diversify its operations but put it under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The terms of the deal, which were announced on Monday, also show that the deal has been amended in recent days: Last Monday, Morgan simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago", explained Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, in Tokyo, "we thought that participation would be entirely made up of ordinary shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves".
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their carrying amount.
And the transaction will result in a dilution of about 20% of earnings per share.
