Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
To rebuild the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, the Bolivian Evo Morales and the Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his colleagues and friends, he was the third to vote on a new constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted 'yes' to the referendum, according to official results with 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" vote was 28%, 7% of the votes were zero and 0.7% were white.
For the draft Constitution to pass, he had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls outside polling stations and a countdown by a non-governmental organisation announced a widespread "yes" victory, with 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed victory over his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly", he said, congratulating Ecuadorians at the governorate headquarters in Guayaquil, 280 kilometres southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was praised by Chávez and Morales as well as his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place quietly under the watchful eye of the Organization of American States (OAS), was on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution gives the state power over the economy, reserving it for the "development planning" of a country that lives primarily on oil extraction by foreign companies and the foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The draft, which was led by Correa, elected in 2006, also gives the head of state increased powers, which can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and have the option of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and run for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also reinforces the principle of free health and education that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
It also provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as the starting point for US drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were held captive for ten days in the desert were returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were released by an Egyptian command in Chad.
The hostages arrived in good shape at around 3.30pm on a special plane at the al-Maza military base, which is being hosted at Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, on a helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are "in good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, said Egypt's Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on September 19 during a 4×4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages had been roamed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It included 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, which organises the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces personnel, who were flown on two helicopters, had launched the attack in the night just before dawn.
"A mutual exchange of fire took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled", said the official, who asked not to be identified.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Lightning Special Forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned the role of secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces in Belgrade, where he is based.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result through the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence, special forces men", he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which the kidnappers were, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army had claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
