The Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, the first European bank in crisis following the snowball effect of the US credit market crisis, by partially nationalising it.
This weekend the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed at the highest level on this issue, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has been widening for more than a year, is for Fortis Bank.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (49%) of the bank's capital in each country.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, including, first of all, the mainly insurance activities it acquired last year from the Dutch body ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a dizzying slump, and in the second half of the week, serious signs of a crisis were already revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell 12 percent, to their lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, the stock has fallen by more than two thirds of its value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around EUR 14 billion, which, according to the company's executives, is unrealistic.
The company's management accuses the uncertainty over the Atlantic over the adoption of the $700 billion US bailout plan of being behind the collapse of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the paper price already enjoyed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the bank's new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
The Belgian government has previously announced that investors should not worry, they will not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in a chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about his or her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There are data protection programmes which link the use of prescription information in all cases to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like giving your chicken to a fox", Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescriptions, told The Washington Post.
Insurance companies depend on the insurance premium and the insurance capital for damage, the health of the client who is present, and if they feel that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent applicants to a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after learning the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, it is easily available from pharmacies, data on the person's drug purchases in the last eighteen months, and from that the program itself determines what disease the person is suffering from and what his health status is.
For example, if a person regularly purchases high doses of cholesterol-lowering medication, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this programme are in circulation, some of which simultaneously determine a risk factor, so there is little left for the insurer to do other than paperwork.
Among the disadvantages of this program is that a drug can be used for different purposes, such as some mixtures can be used for migraine or heat stroke, but they can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others are not.
Companies have developed in data research and analysis, and they must seek patient permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
They are now forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their past wrongdoing.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them to data on drug use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is also becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope is limited to practitioners and insurers.
A bill on widening the scope of the authorities' control over data-providing companies is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and therefore has further developed his programme, which would make data transmission subject to the exclusive consent of the data subject.
The question is whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurers do not sign an insurance contract with him.
So, in the end, the chickens depend on the fox's kindness.
The overall menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme was also on the agenda of the ninth summit alongside other problems, largely global.
Today there will also be a France-India summit where cooperation in the field of nuclear energy will be discussed.
The European Union recognises that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given wider say in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support for New Delhi's candidacy for permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
They did not, however, spend too much time on this issue yesterday at the ninth summit in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, the current President of the European Union, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the Head of the Foreign Affairs Office, Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that within five years they would double trade, which would mean an increase of some 100 billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007 the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious target.
In this respect, they have legally harmonized the 26 bilateral agreements with India on civil aviation, so that air trade can also flourish in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009 at the latest.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's leading trading partner, and New Delhi, the only EU partner in the ninth position.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan has been strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on this issue has been mentioned.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle was also called for, although both play a large part in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate programme, including a target of reducing its toxic emissions by at least 20 per cent by 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as the need to pass a global market at the next year's climate conference, and to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent food prices from rising and supported the call for an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian head of state is today in the French capital, where he is preparing to sign a bilateral agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
In Paris, French companies are expected to receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal is for 15 years.
