According to the data, the importance of books by foreign authors is gradually decreasing in relation to the total Italian production, and in particular, to that for adults and children.
Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The plane wreckage of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau 3,000 meters above sea level in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, no human remains, though.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson cleared the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is indeed the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared", he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (Ntsb) reported that hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the plane: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal effects were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing Fosset's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned himself a place in history through a long series of records.
On his sixth attempt, in 2002, he became the first man to complete a round-the-world flight on a balloon - a two-week solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world without stopping.
Among all the records, he also flew at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
